                        "A **transaction** is \"a group of reads and writes that form a logical unit\"; the word stuck from commercial transactions but does not require ACID. **Transaction processing** simply means low-latency interactive reads/writes, as opposed to periodic **batch processing** (p. 87).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Two access patterns** (p. 87):\n"
                        "\n"
                        "- **OLTP (online transaction processing)**: user-facing apps that look up a small number of records by key using an index, inserting/updating from user input.\n"
                        "- **OLAP (online analytic processing)**: a query scans a huge number of records and computes **aggregates** (count, sum, average) instead of returning raw rows — e.g. \"What was the total revenue of each store in January?\" These feed **business intelligence** reports.\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Table 3-1** contrasts them (p. 88): OLTP reads a small number of records by key, takes random-access low-latency writes from user input, holds the *latest state* of the data, and spans gigabytes-to-terabytes; OLAP aggregates over many records, ingests via **bulk import (ETL)** or an event stream, stores a *history of events*, and spans terabytes-to-petabytes.\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Why a separate database.** SQL works for both, but in the late 1980s and early 1990s companies stopped running analytics on their OLTP systems and built a **data warehouse** (p. 88). OLTP systems must stay highly available and low-latency, so DBAs are \"reluctant to let business analysts run ad-hoc analytic queries\" that scan large parts of the dataset and harm transaction performance. A data warehouse is \"a separate database that analysts can query to their heart's content, without affecting OLTP operations\" — a read-only copy of all the company's OLTP data (p. 88).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**ETL.** Data is **Extract-Transform-Load**ed: extracted (via a periodic dump or a continuous stream), transformed into an analysis-friendly schema, cleaned up, then loaded (pp. 88-89). The big advantage is that the warehouse can be optimized for analytic access — \"the indexing algorithms discussed in the first half of this chapter work well for OLTP, but are not very good at answering analytic queries\" (p. 89). A warehouse and an OLTP database both speak SQL, but their internals diverge, so many vendors now specialize (p. 90). Warehouse vendors include Teradata, Vertica, SAP HANA, and ParAccel (Amazon RedShift is hosted ParAccel), plus SQL-on-Hadoop projects (Hive, Impala, Presto, Drill) inspired by Google's Dremel (p. 90).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Star schema.** Analytics has little data-model diversity; most warehouses use a **star schema** (\"dimensional modeling\") (p. 90). At its center is a **fact table** (e.g. `fact_sales`); each row is an **event** — one product purchased by a customer at a particular time. Capturing individual events maximizes flexibility but makes fact tables enormous — a big enterprise may hold \"tens of petabytes,\" mostly in fact tables (p. 90). Fact columns are either **attributes** (price, cost) or **foreign keys** to **dimension tables** representing the who, what, where, when, how, and why of the event (e.g. `dim_product` with SKU, brand, category; even dates get a `dim_date` so holidays can be flagged) (p. 91). The name comes from the fact table surrounded by dimension tables \"like rays of a star\" (p. 91).\n"
