                        "\n"
                        "Still, they are \"good enough\" as interchange formats — agreeing on the format matters more than its prettiness (p. 111).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "### Binary encodings\n"
                        "\n"
                        "Internally you can use compact binary formats; at terabyte scale the choice matters (p. 111). Many \"binary JSON\" variants exist (**MessagePack**, BSON, ...), but because they keep the JSON data model and prescribe no schema, they must still embed every field name (p. 111). Encoding the example record `{userName: \"Martin\", favoriteNumber: 1337, interests: [...]}` with MessagePack uses **66 bytes vs 81** for whitespace-stripped JSON — a small win for losing human-readability (p. 112).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "### Thrift and Protocol Buffers\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Apache Thrift** (Facebook) and **Protocol Buffers** (Google), both open-sourced 2007-08, require a schema written in an **IDL**, then run **code generation** to produce encode/decode classes (p. 113-114). The key trick: encoded data drops field names and instead stores **field tags** — the numbers from the schema — which act as compact \"aliases for fields\" (p. 114-115).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "Sizes for the same record: Thrift **BinaryProtocol** = 59 bytes; Thrift **CompactProtocol** = 34 bytes (packing field type + tag into one byte and using **variable-length integers** — numbers between -64 and 63 fit in one byte, -8192 to 8191 in two); **Protocol Buffers** = 33 bytes (p. 115-116). `required` vs `optional` makes **no difference to the encoding** — `required` only enables a runtime check that fails if the field is unset (p. 116).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "### Schema evolution with field tags\n"
                        "\n"
                        "- You **can rename** a field (data never stores names) but **cannot change a tag** — that would invalidate all existing encoded data (p. 116).\n"
                        "- **Adding a field:** give it a new tag; old code skips unknown tags by using the datatype annotation to know how many bytes to skip → **forward compatible**. The new field **cannot be `required`** (old data lacks it), so make it optional or give it a default for **backward compatibility** (p. 116-117).\n"
                        "- **Removing a field:** only an optional field (a required field can never be removed), and **never reuse its tag** (p. 117).\n"
                        "- **Changing a datatype** risks truncation/precision loss (e.g. 32-bit → 64-bit integer) (p. 117).\n"
                        "- Protocol Buffers has no list type but a `repeated` marker, so an `optional` field can evolve into a multi-valued `repeated` one; Thrift instead has a real `list` type that supports nesting but not that evolution (p. 117)."
