                        "- **Consistency** is an **application** property: the app's invariants (e.g. credits and debits stay balanced) hold if each transaction preserves them. It is the app's job to define transactions correctly; the DB cannot stop you writing bad data (only specific checks like uniqueness/foreign-key constraints). Hellerstein notes the C was \"tossed in to make the acronym work\" and does not really belong (pp. 216-217).\n"
                        "- **Isolation** means concurrent transactions do not step on each other. The textbook formalization is **serializability**: each transaction can pretend it is the only one running, and the committed result equals some serial order (p. 217). The counter race in Figure 7-1 (two increments take 42 → 43 instead of 44) shows what isolation prevents. But serializable isolation \"is rarely used, because it carries a performance penalty\" — Oracle 11g's \"serializable\" actually implements only snapshot isolation (pp. 217-218).\n"
                        "- **Durability** means that once committed, data survives a crash: written to nonvolatile storage with a write-ahead log, or replicated to some number of nodes (p. 218). But \"perfect durability does not exist\"; disks, fsync and SSDs all have failure modes, so combine writing to disk, replication, and backups (p. 218)."
