                        "When you run a program on **one computer**, it behaves in a \"fairly predictable (deterministic) way: either it works, or it doesn't\" (p. 266). Hardware is hidden behind an **idealized system model** \"that operates with mathematical perfection\": a CPU instruction always does the same thing, and data written to memory or disk stays intact (p. 266). This is deliberate — if an internal fault occurs we prefer the machine to **crash completely** rather than return a wrong result, \"because wrong results are difficult and confusing to deal with\" (p. 266). A single computer is usually \"either fully functional or entirely broken, but not something in between\" (p. 266).\n"
