                        "Each machine has its own **quartz** clock, slightly fast or slow, loosely synced via **NTP** (which itself gets time from a source like a GPS receiver) (p. 279). Computers have two distinct clocks (p. 279-280):\n"
                        "\n"
                        "- **Time-of-day clock** (wall-clock): `clock_gettime(CLOCK_REALTIME)`, `System.currentTimeMillis()` — seconds since the epoch (midnight UTC, 1 Jan 1970), not counting leap seconds. NTP-synced so a timestamp ideally means the same across machines, **but it can jump backwards** when reset, and has historically coarse resolution (10 ms on older Windows). This makes it \"unsuitable for measuring elapsed time\" (p. 280).\n"
                        "- **Monotonic clock**: `clock_gettime(CLOCK_MONOTONIC)`, `System.nanoTime()` — guaranteed to move forward; good for **durations/timeouts**. Its absolute value is meaningless and must not be compared across machines. NTP may **slew** it (speed up/slow by up to 0.05%) but never jump it; resolution is microseconds or better (p. 280).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Synchronization is fickle** (p. 281-282). Google assumes **200 ppm** drift — about 6 ms if resynced every 30 s, or 17 s of drift if resynced once a day. Clocks too far off may be forcibly reset (time jumps); an NTP firewall block can go unnoticed; internet NTP achieves ~35 ms minimum error with occasional ~1 s spikes; some NTP servers are off by hours; **leap seconds** make a minute 59 or 61 s long and \"have crashed many large systems\" (best handled by **smearing** the second over a day); VMs see clock jumps. With effort (GPS, **PTP**), MiFID II requires HFT clocks within **100 µs of UTC** (p. 282).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Ordering events / Last Write Wins** (p. 283-284). In Figure 8-3, even with skew <3 ms, write `x=1` gets timestamp 42.004 while the causally-later `x=2` gets 42.003, so node 2 drops `x=2` and the increment is silently lost. **LWW** (used in Cassandra and Riak) has pitfalls:\n"
                        "\n"
                        "- writes can \"mysteriously disappear\" when a lagging clock can't overwrite a fast clock's value until the skew elapses;\n"
