                        "\n"
                        "With tight NTP, a packet can still appear to arrive (recipient's clock 99 ms) before it was sent (sender's 100 ms) (p. 284). **Logical clocks** (incrementing counters) are a safer ordering mechanism than these **physical clocks**.\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Confidence intervals** (p. 285). A clock reading is really \"a range of times, within a confidence interval\" (e.g. 95% sure between 10.3 and 10.5 s); if you only know time ±100 ms, the microsecond digits are meaningless. Most APIs hide this; **Google's TrueTime** (Spanner) instead returns `[earliest, latest]`.\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Spanner's global snapshots** (p. 285-286) use TrueTime: if two intervals don't overlap (`A.latest < B.earliest`) then B definitely happened after A; if they overlap, order is unknown. To guarantee causal timestamps, Spanner **deliberately waits out the confidence-interval width** before committing a read-write transaction. To keep that wait short, Google deploys a GPS or atomic clock in each datacenter, syncing within about **7 ms**."
