                        "\n"
                        "**Implementing it** (pp. 323-324): **single-leader** is *potentially* linearizable (read from the leader or synchronous followers), but a \"delusional\" old leader violates it; **consensus algorithms** are linearizable (they prevent split brain and stale replicas — ZooKeeper, etcd); **multi-leader** is not; **leaderless** is *probably not* — last-write-wins clocks and sloppy quorums ruin it. Even a **strict quorum** (`w + r > n`) is not linearizable (Figure 9-6): with variable delays one reader can see the new value while a later reader sees the old (p. 325). You can recover linearizability only at a performance cost (synchronous read repair, writer reads latest quorum), and a linearizable `cas` still needs consensus (p. 325).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**The cost — CAP.** When the network partitions, a linearizable system must choose: replicas cut off from the others must block or error (become unavailable); a non-linearizable system (e.g. multi-leader) lets each replica keep serving. This is the **CAP theorem** (Brewer, 2000) (p. 327). Kleppmann argues the \"pick 2 of 3\" framing is misleading — partitions are a fault you do not choose — and prefers **\"Consistent or Available when Partitioned\"** (p. 327). Formally CAP is narrow: it covers only one consistency model (linearizability) and one fault (network partitions), so it is of mostly historical value (p. 327).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Linearizability is just slow**, even with no faults (p. 328). Even multicore RAM is not linearizable (caches/store buffers) — and there the reason for dropping it is **performance, not fault tolerance**. Attiya & Welch prove the response time of linearizable reads/writes is \"at least proportional to the uncertainty of delays in the network\" (p. 328); no faster algorithm exists, but weaker models can be much faster."
