                {
                    "slug": "databases-and-streams",
                    "title": "Databases and Streams: CDC, Event Sourcing, and Immutability",
                    "source_refs": "DDIA pp.436-448",
                    "body_md": (
                        "A write to a database is itself an event. A **replication log** is \"a stream of database write events\" produced by the leader; followers apply it in order to converge — **state machine replication** (p.437). The problem: no single system serves all needs, so an app runs an OLTP database, a cache, a search index, and a warehouse, each holding its own copy that must be **kept in sync** (p.437).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Dual writes** (the app writes to each system itself) are broken (p.438). Concurrent writes can leave systems permanently inconsistent — the database ends at B while the index ends at A (Fig 11-4) — and one write may succeed while another fails (an atomic-commit problem). There is no single leader ordering the writes.\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Change Data Capture (CDC)** fixes this: \"the process of observing all data changes written to a database, and extracting them\" as a stream (p.439). CDC makes one database the **leader** and turns the others into **followers**; a log-based broker preserves the change order. Implementations: triggers (fragile, slow) or parsing the replication log — LinkedIn Databus, Facebook Wormhole, Bottled Water (Postgres WAL), Maxwell/Debezium (MySQL binlog), Mongoriver (oplog), GoldenGate (Oracle) (p.440). CDC is **asynchronous**, so replication-lag issues apply. To bootstrap you need a consistent **initial snapshot** tied to a known log offset (p.440-441). **Log compaction** keeps only the most recent value per key (a null value is a tombstone), so disk usage depends on current contents, not write count — letting a new consumer rebuild a full copy from offset 0 (Kafka supports this) (p.441).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Event sourcing** applies the idea at a higher level of abstraction (p.442): the application is built directly on **immutable events** in an append-only store; updates and deletes are prohibited. Unlike CDC (low-level row changes; each event carries the full new record for a key), event-sourcing events express the **intent** of a user action, so later events do *not* overwrite earlier ones — you need the full history and cannot compact it the same way (p.442-443). State is derived by a **deterministic** replay; snapshots are only a read/recovery optimization. The model distinguishes **commands** from **events**: a command may fail validation (e.g. the seat is already taken); once accepted it becomes an immutable **event/fact** that consumers cannot reject — so validation must happen *synchronously*, before the event is emitted (p.443-444).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**State, streams, and immutability** (p.444-445): mutable state is the *result* of the events that mutated it — they are \"two sides of the same coin.\" Mathematically, state is the **integral** of the event stream over time, and a change stream is the **derivative** of the state (Fig 11-6). As Pat Helland puts it: \"The truth is the log. The database is a cache of a subset of the log.\" Immutability mirrors accounting ledgers — mistakes are fixed with **compensating** transactions, never erasure — and it captures extra information (a cart add-then-remove tells you something a plain delete would lose) (p.445-446).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "Separating the immutable log from mutable state lets you derive **several read views** from one event log and run new and old views side by side — known as **CQRS** (command query responsibility segregation) (p.446). Downsides: consumers are asynchronous, so **reading your own writes** is not guaranteed (p.447). And *true* deletion is hard despite immutability (Datomic *excision*, Fossil *shunning*), because copies live in storage engines, SSDs, and backups (p.447-448)."
                    ),
                    "key_takeaways": [
                        "Dual writes cause inconsistency; CDC makes one database the leader and streams its ordered changelog to derived systems.",
                        "Log compaction (latest value per key, tombstones) lets a consumer rebuild a full dataset from offset 0.",
                        "Event sourcing stores immutable, intent-level events; current state is a deterministic replay, and commands are validated before becoming events.",
                        "The log is the source of truth and the database is a cache; one log can feed many read views (CQRS).",
                    ],
                },
